    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ef488ed7_86be7c26",
        "filename": "handler/handler_main.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 317,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-03T20:10:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I don\u0027t fully know how reset_own_crash_exception_port_to_system_default is used, but just confirming that it\u0027s OK not to pass it through here?\n\nYeah, intentional. Since exception ports are inherited, if the first instance reset its exception ports to the system default, that’ll remain in effect for the second instance. I could add a comment if you think it’d be useful.\n\nBackground: --reset-own-crash-exception-port-to-system-default is useful in certain cases where Chrome restarts itself. The new Chrome winds up a child process of the original Chrome, and inherits the original Chrome’s exception ports. That means that the new Chrome’s crashpad_handler will also, in turn, be hooked up to the original Chrome’s crashpad_handler, which prevents the original Chrome’s crashpad_handler from ever exiting. In real life, the proces model is slightly more complex than that because we can’t have two Chromes running simultaneously, but that’s the gist of it. This option breaks a link in that chain.",
      "parentUuid": "031038bf_d2d82837",
      "revId": "427d0b8e50b55735ad5d3dd0e8d158fbcc099aeb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3d844a72_54121494",
        "filename": "handler/handler_main.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 319,
      "author": {
        "id": 1177549
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-03T20:14:35Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This wouldn\u0027t work for Chrome on Windows, as it needs a --type\u003dcrashpad-handler argument to dispatch towards Crashpad. It also needs a /prefetch: argument to get through the eye of the needle to even get there.\nI think the same would be true for e.g. setup.exe and other Windows users of Crashpad.\nI had started on a CL \u003chttps://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/450985/\u003e to crack the main function into a class, which would make a reasonable hookup point for Crashpad embedders to add \"adornments\" for call-outs and for e.g. command line generation/extension.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 319,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 319,
        "endChar": 47
      },
      "revId": "427d0b8e50b55735ad5d3dd0e8d158fbcc099aeb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f7b0e9ca_4c401d82",
        "filename": "handler/handler_main.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 319,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-03T20:23:58Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e This wouldn\u0027t work for Chrome on Windows, as it needs a --type\u003dcrashpad-handler argument to dispatch towards Crashpad.\n\nThat’s what the optional argument to --monitor-self is for. The idea was to have Chrome start the handler with --monitor-self\u003d--type\u003dcrashpad-handler.\n\n\u003e It also needs a /prefetch: argument to get through the eye of the needle to even get there.\n\nI forgot about /prefetch:, but I thought that it was optional?\n\nIf it’s not…\n\nI could make monitor_self_arg a std::vector\u003cstd::string\u003e and accumulate arguments into it. But having multiple --monitor-self arguments starts to get weird enough that it’s probably worth splitting the big --monitor-self switch up and dedicating --monitor-self-argument to accumulate arguments.\n\nThen we could do --monitor-self --monitor-self-argument\u003d--type\u003dcrashpad_handler --monitor-self-argument\u003d/prefetch:7",
      "parentUuid": "3d844a72_54121494",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 319,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 319,
        "endChar": 47
      },
      "revId": "427d0b8e50b55735ad5d3dd0e8d158fbcc099aeb",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
